# PR conventions

- Treat commit and PR as two explicit, separate user-driven phases.
- Do not create a commit unless the user explicitly asks for a commit.
- Before committing, summarize staged + unstaged changes and propose a commit message for user confirmation.
- When creating pull requests, use `.github/pull_request_template.md` when this repo has one.
- Fill every section of the PR template. If not applicable, write `N/A` (do not leave sections blank).
- Before any remote action, show the proposed PR title/body generated from current branch changes and template sections.
- Require explicit user approval before `git push -u origin HEAD`.
- After push output is confirmed, require a second explicit user approval before `gh pr create`.
- Keep **Why** focused on the outcome/problem, not just file changes.
- In **Todo Mapping**, reference relevant items from `../haderach-tasks/tasks/` with task ID and title.
- In **Validation**, list only checks that were actually run.
- If generated files or repo-specific build artifacts are part of the workflow, include them in **Validation** when they were regenerated or verified.
- In **Deploy / Ops Notes**, explicitly call out the relevant deploy surfaces, backend/services, and any auth/IAM/secret implications.
- Keep PRs small and single-purpose when possible.

## Platform-local additions

- If requirements docs changed in `haderach-platform`, include requirements-specific validation in **Validation** (catalog regeneration, sync to hosting, and `tab=requirements`/`project=` behavior checks).
- In **Deploy / Ops Notes** for `haderach-platform`, explicitly call out Firebase Hosting, Cloud Run/docs, and any auth/IAP/secret implications.
